      <!-- Section 5: What to look for -->
      <section id="what-to-look-for">
        <span class="eyebrow">Evaluation guide</span>
        <h2 class="anchor-top !mt-3">How to Choose an AI Visibility Monitoring Platform: Six Criteria for Marketing Leaders</h2>
        <p class="mt-4 max-w-2xl text-ink-300 leading-relaxed"><strong>Six criteria determine whether an AI visibility monitoring platform will produce board-reportable data and competitive insight — or simply generate dashboard numbers disconnected from commercial decisions.</strong> This is a buying framework for marketing leaders evaluating category-level monitoring platforms. For practitioners who need to assess tools on citation granularity, sampling methodology, and prompt-set design, see the <a href="/best-llm-visibility-tools/" class="text-accent-400 underline decoration-accent-500/30 underline-offset-2 hover:text-accent-300">LLM citation monitoring tools guide</a>.</p>

        <div class="mt-8 grid gap-6 sm:grid-cols-2">
          <div class="card p-6">
            <h3 class="font-display text-base font-semibold text-ink-50">1. Platform breadth</h3>
            <p class="mt-2 text-sm leading-relaxed text-ink-300">Does the tool cover the four minimum platforms: ChatGPT, Perplexity, Gemini, and Copilot? A tool that only monitors one or two platforms is measuring a partial picture of AI answer visibility. Your audience uses multiple AI tools; your tracking should reflect that. Check whether the vendor's roadmap includes platforms you consider strategically important.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="card p-6">
            <h3 class="font-display text-base font-semibold text-ink-50">2. Custom prompt libraries</h3>
            <p class="mt-2 text-sm leading-relaxed text-ink-300">Can you build your own prompt library using the queries your actual customers use? Generic preset prompts will not reflect your specific business context. Tools that allow you to organise prompts by intent type, persona, or topic cluster produce data that maps directly to your content and commercial strategy rather than generic category-level observations.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="card p-6">
            <h3 class="font-display text-base font-semibold text-ink-50">3. Historical data retention</h3>
            <p class="mt-2 text-sm leading-relaxed text-ink-300">How far back does the tool retain data, and can you access trend lines rather than just current snapshots? Without historical data, you cannot determine whether a change in citation frequency resulted from your optimisation work, a platform model update, or a competitor's campaign. Minimum useful retention is ninety days; twelve months is the standard for serious programmes.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="card p-6">
            <h3 class="font-display text-base font-semibold text-ink-50">4. Citation vs. mention distinction</h3>
            <p class="mt-2 text-sm leading-relaxed text-ink-300">Does the tool distinguish between a direct citation (your URL named as a source) and an incidental brand mention (your name appears in the answer text without a source link)? These are different signals with different implications. Conflating them inflates apparent visibility and obscures where genuine citation work needs to be done.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="card p-6">
            <h3 class="font-display text-base font-semibold text-ink-50">5. Data methodology transparency</h3>
            <p class="mt-2 text-sm leading-relaxed text-ink-300">Is the vendor transparent about how they query AI platforms, how many samples per prompt they take, and how they handle the inherent variability in AI responses? Vendors who are vague about their methodology are a yellow flag; robust statistical sampling with documented confidence intervals is the standard you should expect from tools you are using for strategic decision-making.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="card p-6">
            <h3 class="font-display text-base font-semibold text-ink-50">6. Competitive benchmarking</h3>
            <p class="mt-2 text-sm leading-relaxed text-ink-300">Can you track named competitors alongside your own brand using the same prompt library? Absolute citation rates are useful, but relative share-of-voice — knowing that you are cited in 35% of relevant queries while your primary competitor is cited in 58% — is what drives prioritisation decisions and communicates the opportunity clearly to business stakeholders.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </section>

